The Brooks Range has seen a few swarms recently. The Noatak swarm the eastern Brooks Range last year, and the ongoing Purcell Mountains swarm. There was also a swarm near the Pribilof Islands in 2015. But we don't know yet exactly why some earthquake sequences happen as swarms.

Swarms don't work like that. An earthquake swarm has no clear mainshock. Instead, it churns out a number of earthquakes of comparable size over days or months, with a lot of smaller quakes thrown in. Compare the Iniskin graphs in the last tweet to the 2014 Noatak swarm. https://t.co/2NqYZEpNJl

Short version: In a mainshock-aftershock sequence, a large earthquake initiates a series of much smaller quakes that tapers off over time. For example, here's the 2016 M7.1 Iniskin sequence from its start through the end of 2016. https://t.co/ycUjWpsmBb

The Purcell Mountains swarm is still going, with a M4.7 at 9:07 last night. It was felt in Huslia. Last week, we posted a short article to our website explaining how a swarm is different from the more common mainshock-aftershock type of sequence. https://t.co/DThjtkcHeH
